>Adrian,
>
>Sounds to me like your choke is adjusted all of the way shut,
>meaning no
>air. Thus no spark, no fire.  I used to be a devout "no choke" kind
>of guy,
>but my mechanic steered me toward the other way(This is for a stock
>carb
>right?).  I now run a Progressive with no choke(Just because I
>haven't
>looked into the correct way to set it up), but when I had the stock
>carb, I
>followed these steps:
>
>Check to see if the choke is all the way closed when the engine is
>cold.
>
>1. make sure the power is connected correctly
>2. With the engine cool, take off the air cleaner, and loosen the
>choke hold
>down screws(3).
>3. I believe there is a notch in the white choke body that needs to
>be lined
>up with a hash mark on the "hold-down" ring.
>
>This forces the choke to close at a certain amount, until the engine
>warms
>up and makes an internal spring inside the choke mechanism to grow,
>opening
>the choke.
>
>I can get more specific when I get home, and take a look at my stock
>engine.
>
> - Hope this helps.
>
>Kevin Albrecht
>Build your own reality...
>www.dbsitebuilder.net
